===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# {{lb|en|zoology}} The [[scale]], or [[exopodite]], of an [[antenna]] of a [[crustacean]].
# {{lb|en|medicine}} A [[flake]] of dead [[skin]] tissue.
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1984| title=In Vivo Diverse Spectrum of Neoplasms Induced in 30-day-old Rats and in Vitro Neoplastic Transformation of Rat Mammary Epithelial Cells Following a Single Pulse of N-Ethyl-N-Nitrosourea|author=Gheorghe Stoica | page=113| passage=EGF increased proliferation and '''squame''' formation and induced keratinization in cultured MA cells, an observation heretofore not reported in rat MA cells. }}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=2009| title=Weedon's Skin Pathology |author=David Weedon | page=248| passage=They flatten further and become compacted into a dense keratinous layer known as the stratum corneum. The superficial flake-like '''squames''' are eventually cast off (desquamate). }}
#* '''2011''', Terence Allen and Graham Cowling, ''The Cell: A Very Short Introduction'', Oxford 2011, p. 80:
#*: '''Squames''' begin life as normal cells in the lower layers of the epidermis but, as they travel towards the surface, they progressively lose all recognizable contents, becoming plates of mainly keratin protein, based on a progressive deposition of protein on the intermediate filaments of the cytoskeleton.
# {{lb|en|medicine}} A [[squamous]] ([[scale]]-like) cell.
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1928 | title=Journal of the Cancer Research Committee of the University of Sydney, Volume 1|author=| page=210| passage=Here the invading cell masses of the cancer consist of short thick '''squames''', and the nearest approach to cell nest formation may be only a whorling of those '''squames''' in the centres of the cell masses.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1961| title=Novak's Textbook of Gynecology |author=Edmund R. Novak, ‎Georgeanna Seegar Jones | page=766| passage=Second, if it is a '''squame''', the nuclear size and chromatin pattern are determined. If the nucleus of this '''squame''' is plump and vesicular with an intact chromatin pattern, the cell is an intermediate; if it is pyknotic, shrunken, and hyperchromatic and lacks chromatin pattern, the cell is a superficial. }}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=2011| title=Clinical Canine and Feline Reproduction: Evidence-Based Answers|author=Margaret V. Root Kustritz | page=7| passage=As the cells divide and the vaginal lining thickens, the cells nearest the lumen become nonviable and lose the characteristic appearance of a healthy cell monolayer. The misshapen, clumped cells are termed cornified. Specific cell types are superficial cells and anuclear '''squame''' cells (Fig. 2-2). }}
# {{lb|en|anatomy}} A [[bony]] [[plate]].
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1991| title=The Skulls, Endocasts, and Teeth of Homo Habilis|author=Phillip V. Tobias | page=84| passage=Most of the right temporal bone is well-preserved, with the exception of much of the zygoma and the upper edge of the temporal '''squame''' (Plate 8).}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=2003| title=South African Journal of Science - Volume 99, Issues 1-6 |author=| page=219| passage=A tapering of the fragment on its inner surface, and the pattern of branching of the middle meningeal vessel grooves, have enabled us to identify the piece as most probably part of the left temporal '''squame''' of a cranium.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=2007| title=Evolutionary History of the "Robust" Australopithecines |author=Frederick E. Grine | page=287| passage=Thus, the frontal fragment displays a slight concavity of the frontal '''squame''' behind glabella, a thin and flattened supra-orbital margin, and marked encroachment of the temporal lines just posterior to the supra-orbital margin. }}

